<figure
  class="hamjepa-concept-diagram"
  aria-labelledby="hamjepa-symplectic-map-title"
  aria-describedby="hamjepa-symplectic-map-caption"
>
  <div class="hamjepa-concept-scroll" tabindex="0" aria-label="Scrollable symplectic comparison diagram">
    <svg
      class="hamjepa-concept-svg"
      viewBox="0 0 980 760"
      role="img"
      aria-labelledby="hamjepa-symplectic-map-title hamjepa-symplectic-map-desc"
      preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet"
    >
      <title id="hamjepa-symplectic-map-title">Generic map versus symplectic map geometry</title>
      <desc id="hamjepa-symplectic-map-desc">
        Top panel shows generic learned map with strong local-volume collapse into a thin ribbon. Bottom panel shows
        symplectic map that deforms shape while preserving phase-space volume.
      </desc>

      <defs>
        <marker id="ham-sym-arrow" markerWidth="9" markerHeight="9" refX="7.6" refY="4.5" orient="auto">
          <path d="M0,0 L9,4.5 L0,9 z" fill="#4d5866" />
        </marker>
      </defs>

      <text x="490" y="52" class="t-head" text-anchor="middle">generic learned map</text>
      <rect x="112" y="86" width="312" height="214" rx="14" class="panel panel-generic" />
      <path
        d="M176 204 C202 140 282 122 350 146 C394 160 414 204 396 242 C370 286 290 294 226 270 C190 258 162 236 176 204 Z"
        class="state state-start"
      />
      <line x1="434" y1="194" x2="542" y2="194" class="a-main" marker-end="url(#ham-sym-arrow)" />
      <rect x="552" y="86" width="312" height="214" rx="14" class="panel panel-generic" />
      <path
        d="M616 194 C700 186 760 184 826 188 C836 190 838 198 828 200 C760 206 700 206 616 198 C606 196 606 194 616 194 Z"
        class="state state-collapse"
      />

      <text x="490" y="404" class="t-head" text-anchor="middle">symplectic map</text>
      <rect x="112" y="438" width="312" height="214" rx="14" class="panel panel-symplectic" />
      <path
        d="M176 556 C202 492 282 474 350 498 C394 512 414 556 396 594 C370 638 290 646 226 622 C190 610 162 588 176 556 Z"
        class="state state-start"
      />
      <line x1="434" y1="546" x2="542" y2="546" class="a-main" marker-end="url(#ham-sym-arrow)" />
      <rect x="552" y="438" width="312" height="214" rx="14" class="panel panel-symplectic" />
      <path
        d="M620 548 C640 492 708 470 772 490 C824 506 844 560 818 606 C784 642 724 642 672 620 C628 602 604 578 620 548 Z"
        class="state state-symplectic"
      />
    </svg>
  </div>

  <figcaption id="hamjepa-symplectic-map-caption" class="hamjepa-concept-caption">
    <strong>What “symplectic” means geometrically.</strong> A generic learned map can bend, stretch, and arbitrarily
    collapse local geometry. A symplectic map can still deform the state space, but it preserves total phase-space
    volume locally, i.e. |det DΦ|=1. This gives the predictor a structured notion of reversibility and ensures that
    the predictor itself is not the source of volume collapse.
  </figcaption>
</figure>

